---


Author Name: **Jeremy Bennett** (@jeremybennett)
Original Redmine Message: 1041 from https://www.veripool.org



---

I'm about to try implementing the SystemVerilog 'alias' keyword. This is similar to continuous assignment, but it is bi-directional, so useful with inouts. IEEE 1800-2012 gives the example

```
module swap (
	     inout wire [31:0] a,
	     inout wire [31:0] b
	     );

    alias {a[7:0],a[15:8],a[23:16],a[31:24]} = b;

endmodule

```

to swap the bytes of a pair of inputs. This is fundamentally a synonym, and it would be nice to think that a simple substitution of one name with the other would suffice. However that leads to nonsense syntax for non-trivial cases. The example above would become:

```
module swap (
	     inout wire [31:0] a,
	     inout wire [31:0] {a[7:0],a[15:8],a[23:16],a[31:24]}
	     );

endmodule

```

which is not valid SystemVerilog. One approach which seems to work is to rewrite as a pair of continuous assignments:

```
module swap (
	     inout wire [31:0] a,
	     inout wire [31:0] b
	     );

    // alias {a[7:0],a[15:8],a[23:16],a[31:24]} = b;

    wire [31:0] a_prime;
    wire [31:0] b_prime;

    assign b_prime = {a[7:0],a[15:8],a[23:16],a[31:24]};
    assign {a_prime[7:0],a_prime[15:8],a_prime[23:16],a_prime[31:24]} = b;
    assign b = b_prime;
    assign a = a_prime;

endmodule

```

We do seem to need the intermediate variables a_prime and b_prime. Without these, although Verilator accepts the code, it complains about UNOPTFLAT,and if that is ignored fails to make the transform.

I can't help feeling there must be a much simpler approach, since Verilator already does a great deal of internal aliasing when it flattens the module hierarchy. Any ideas welcome.

